               <msContents>
                  <summary>Fine Psalter from high social location with full-color illuminations</summary>
                  <msItem xml:id="ms_i1"><locus from="3r" to="146v" facs="003">Fols 3r–146v</locus><title type="complete" ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LIT2701Dawit"> On <locus target="#2v" facs="003">fol. 2v</locus>, the copyist has included two popular poems that often appear at the head of the Psalms, “Come to me, David, King of Israel,” and “The Psalms of David are like a garden.”</title>
                  <textLang mainLang="gez">Gǝ'ǝz</textLang>
                  <msItem xml:id="ms_i1.1"><locus from="3r" to="116v" facs="003">Fols 3r–116v</locus><title type="complete" ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LIT2000Mazmur">Mazmura Dāwit</title>
                  <textLang mainLang="gez">Gǝ'ǝz</textLang>
                </msItem>
                  <msItem xml:id="ms_i1.2"><locus from="116v" to="129r" facs="117">Fols 116v–129r</locus><title type="complete" ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LIT1828Mahale">Book of Odes</title>
                  <textLang mainLang="gez">Gǝ'ǝz</textLang>
                </msItem>
                  <msItem xml:id="ms_i1.3"><locus from="129r" to="135v" facs="129">Fols 129r–135v</locus><title type="complete" ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LIT2362Songof">, common edition</title>
                  <textLang mainLang="gez">Gǝ'ǝz</textLang>
                </msItem>
                  <msItem xml:id="ms_i1.4"><locus from="136r" to="143r" facs="136">Fols 136r–143r</locus><title type="complete" ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LIT2509Weddas">, arranged for the days of the week</title>
                  <textLang mainLang="gez">Gǝ'ǝz</textLang>
                </msItem>
                  <msItem xml:id="ms_i1.5"><locus from="143v" to="146v" facs="144">Fols 143v–146v</locus><title type="complete" ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LIT1113Anqasa">ʾAnqaṣa
                                                  bǝrhān</title>
                  <textLang mainLang="gez">Gǝ'ǝz</textLang>
                </msItem>
              </msItem>
               </msContents>
               <physDesc>
                  <objectDesc form="Codex">
                     <supportDesc>
                        <extent>
                           <measure unit="leaf">147</measure>
                           <dimensions type="outer" unit="mm">
                              <height>185</height>
                              <width>140</width>
                              <depth>60</depth>
                           </dimensions>
                        </extent>
                     </supportDesc>
                     <layoutDesc>
                       <layout columns="1" writtenLines="22">
                         <locus from="2r" to="135v" facs="002">Fols 2r–135v</locus>
                       </layout>
                       <layout columns="2" writtenLines="27">
                         <locus from="136r" to="146v" facs="136">Fols 136r–146v</locus>
                       </layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc>
                  <handNote xml:id="h1" script="Ethiopic">
                  <seg type="rubrication">
                  <foreign xml:lang="gez">ኢግዚአብሔር፡</foreign>
                  </seg>
                  <desc>The word for God is systematically rubricated</desc>
                  <desc><title type="complete" ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LIT2000Mazmur#Ps150">Psalms of
                                                  David, Psalmus 150</title> and the 10th biblical canticle show columetric rubrication</desc>
                  </handNote>
                  </handDesc>
                  <decoDesc>
                    <decoNote type="miniature" xml:id="d1"><locus target="#2r" facs="002">Fol. 2r</locus><desc>A full-color illumination of <ref type="authFile" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/AT1066DavidHarp">David Playing the Harp</ref>, with patron prostrate beneath. David is depicted wearing shoes with curling toes as well as wearing a very fine <term key="crown" ana="#crown"/>. A curtain of colorful cloth covers the illumination with caption (mostly effaced) <q>“How. . . </q></desc></decoNote>
                    <decoNote type="miniature" xml:id="d2"><locus target="#2v" facs="003">Fol. 2v</locus><desc>Full-color illuminations of a talismanic figure in the shape of a four pointed <ref type="authFile" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/AT1071Cross">Cross</ref> with a face in the center, and a lion embracing a staff with tri-color flags in the lower right of the folio</desc></decoNote>
                    <decoNote type="miniature" xml:id="d3"><locus target="#147r #148r" facs="147 148">Fols. 147r, 148r</locus><desc>Full-color illuminations of <ref type="authFile" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/AT1031VirginAndChild">Virgin and Child</ref> with two <term key="angel" ana="#angel"/>s handing flowers to <persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS6819Mary">St Mary</persName>; a patron stands below and to the left. Mary and the baby gaze at him and Mary extends a hand <term key="cross" ana="#cross"/>. Mary’s shoes have curling toes.  A curtain of colorful cloth covers the illumination. A caption lies below but is indecipherable</desc></decoNote>
                  </decoDesc>
                  <additions>
                  <list>
                    <item xml:id="e1">
                    <desc>
                    Several characteristics of the book suggest a private, but high social location: Fine leather binding, with headband and tailband, carefully trimmed and stitched, with high quality fabric visible between the turndowns, fine and intricate illuminations with curtains, colorful harags, and fine copying
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="a1">
                    <locus target="#1v" facs="002">Fol. 1v</locus>
                    <desc type="OwnershipNote">
                    Note of secondary ownership, written in red ink
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="e2">
                    <desc>
                    Each group of ten Psalms is headed by some sort of indication like a line of alternating red and black dots or a colorful harag
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="e3">
                    <locus target="#58v" facs="059">Fol. 58v</locus>The midpoint of the Psalms is unmarked
                    <desc>
                    The midpoint of the Psalms is unmarked
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="e4">
                    <desc>
                    The sections of <title type="complete" ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LIT2000Mazmur#Ps118">Psalms of
                                                  David, Psalmus 118</title> are marked only with a transliterated Hebrew letter, written in red ink
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="a2">
                    <desc>
                    <title type="complete" ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LIT2000Mazmur#Ps151">Psalms of
                                                  David, Psalmus 151</title> contains all four plusses of the long text
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="a3">
                    <locus target="#77r" facs="077">Fol. 77r</locus>
                    <desc>
                    Scribal doxology, at the end of <title type="complete" ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LIT2000Mazmur#Ps100">Psalms of
                                                  David, Psalmus 100</title>: <foreign xml:lang="gez">ስብሐት ለአብ ወወልድ ወመንፈስ ቅዱስ። ለዓለም ወለዓለመ ዓለም። ዝኒ ተፍባሚተ መዝሙር ዘ፻።</foreign>
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="a4">
                    <locus target="#116v" facs="117">Fol. 116v</locus>
                    <desc>
                    Doxology at the end of <title type="complete" ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LIT2000Mazmur#Ps151">Psalms of
                                                  David, Psalmus 151</title>:  <foreign xml:lang="gez">ስብሐት ለአብ ወወልድ ወመንፈስ ቅዱስ።</foreign>, written in a secondary hand
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="a5">
                    <desc>
                    The superscription to the fourth biblical canticle is “Prayer of Hana, Mother of Samuel, prophet.”
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="a6">
                    <locus target="#136v" facs="137">Fol. 136v</locus>
                    <desc type="OwnershipNote">
                    note of secondary ownership: This Dawit belongs to Abba Walda Tensa’e, written in a different hand
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="a7">
                    <locus target="#136v" facs="137">Fol. 136v</locus>
                    <desc>
                    Scribal doxology, at the end of the Song of Songs: <foreign xml:lang="gez">ስብሐት ለአብ ወወልድ ወመንፈስ ቅዱስ። ለዓለም ወለዓ(ለ)መ ዓለም። በዝየ ተፈጸመ መኃልያ ሰሎሞን።</foreign>
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="a8">
                    <locus target="#136v" facs="137">Fol. 136v</locus>
                    <desc>
                    First lines for the introductory prayer for the recitation of Praises of Mary, written in a different, trained hand
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="a9">
                    <desc>
                    <title type="complete" ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LIT2509Weddas">Wǝddāse
                                                  Māryām</title> are laid out beginning on Monday and culminating on Sunday
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="a10">
                    <locus target="#146v" facs="147">Fol. 146v</locus>
                    <desc>
                    Scribal Prayer of thanksgiving, <foreign xml:lang="gez">ይትባረክ፡ እግዚአብሔር፡ አምላኪየ፡ ዘመሐሮን፡ ጽሕፈተ፡ ለእደውየ፡ ወጥበበ፤ ለአፃብዕየ። ወዘአፈጸመኒ፡ ዘንተ፡ መዝሙረ ዳዊት፡ እምጥንቱ፡ እስከ፡ ተፍጻሜቱ፡ በዳህና፡ ወበሰላም፡ ለዓለም፡ አሜን።</foreign>  Blessed be my God who taught writing for my hand, wisdom for my finger [echoing <title type="complete" ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LIT2000Mazmur#Ps151">Psalms of
                                                  David, Psalmus 151</title>], who helped me to finish this Psalter from beginning to end, in peace and health, forever, Amen
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                  </list>
                  </additions>
                  <bindingDesc>
                    <binding xml:id="binding" contemporary="true">
                      <decoNote xml:id="b1" type="bindingMaterial">
                        <material key="parchment"/>
                        <material key="wood"/>
                        <material key="leather"/>
                      </decoNote>
                    </binding>
                  </bindingDesc>
               </physDesc>
               <history>
                  <origin>
                     <origDate notBefore="1900" notAfter="1950">Early-twentieth century</origDate>
                  </origin>
               </history>
            </msDesc>
         </sourceDesc>
